did.abstract: The C. Darwin Stolzenbach papers consists of correspondence and memoranda, bound and unbound reports, original and photocopied news clippings, documents related to civil action suits pertaining to highway legislation, excerpts from law review magazines, press releases, copies of speeches, minutes and agendas of meetings, original and photocopied Congressional and other legislation, photographs, and maps.

prefercite.head: Preferred citation
prefercite.p: C. Darwin Stolzenbach papers, Special Collections Research Center, The George Washington University.

acqinfo.head: Acquisition Information
acqinfo.p: The bulk of the collection was donated to the Gelman Library in 1989, with another major accretion coming in 1991. Future accretions to the collection are not anticipated.

userestrict.head: Restrictions on Use
userestrict.p: Some material may be copyrighted or restricted. It is the patron's obligation to determine and satisfy copyright or other case restrictions when publishing or otherwise distributing materials found in the collections.

bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The C. Darwin Stolzenbach papers relate to the history of WMATA and of regional mass transportation. The material dates from 1930 through 1988, with only one item, a report in Washington traffic problems, dating from 1930. The bulk of the documents date from 1960 to 1969. Documents dating from 1979 through 1988 are related primarily to Stolzenbach's three-year tenure as Chairman and President of the Institute for the Study of Transportation

The Papers were the private collection of C. Darwin Stolzenbach, accumulated over the course of twenty-five years. Information as to how he acquired many of those documents (such as related to the reading files and the civil action suits) is absent from either the donor file or Stolzenbach's personal correspondence. All rights, such as they were held by the donor at the time of transfer, were transferred to the George Washington University at the time of donation. Further, no restrictions on the use of the documents in the collection were made by the donor at the times of tranfer.

The C. Darwin Stolzenbach Papers, together with four other manuscript collections, were processed under a grant from the National Historic Publications and Records Commission. The grant, entitled "The Nation's Hometown History" was awarded in the fall of 1990. This collection complements other Department of Special Collections holdings related to the history of WMATA and of regional mass transportation. Relevant manuscript collections for further research include the: Cody Pfanstiehl Papers, WMATA Metro History Project Collection, WMATA Metrorail Specifications Collection, and Greater Washington Board of Trade Records.

C. Darwin Stolzenbach, who changed his last name to Fairweather sometime during the early 1980's, studied physics at MIT from 1932 to 1935. Soon thereafter, he moved to the Washington area, attending the George Washington University from 1939 to 1935, where he studied political science, and the American University from 1941 to 1942, studying public administration.

From 1941 to 1944 he served in the Office of the Chief of Engineers in the United States Army Air Forces as a program analyst. Following that, for four years beginning in 1944, Stolzenbach worked as an economist in the Bureau of the Budget, and beginning in 1948 as Special Assistant to the Secretary of Commerce for Transportation Policy Planning. In 1951 he became a senior operations research analyst at the Johns Hopkins University's Operations Research Office. There he conducted assessments of the defense of the United States from attack by missiles and bombers.

In 1961, Stolzenbach was named by President Kennedy to replace H. Holmes Vogel as Administrator of the National Capital Transportation Agency (NCTA), who had himself been appointed by President Eisenhower. Until his resignation in 1965, Stolzenbach oversaw the development and application of a comprehensive highway and mass transit plan for the National Capital region. By 1965, the NCTA had laid the foundations for a subway system and drafted plans for the proposed Inner Loop, I-266, and Three Sisters Bridge projects. In his letter of resignation, Stolzenbach made it clear that the research and operations analysis having been completed, Stolzenbach believed that he had guided the NCTA through those phases that required his expertise. He was succeeded by Walter McCarter.

As an advisory agency, the NCTA did not actually implement the plans that it proposed. That job fell to the Department of Transportation. However, the Agency did conduct extensive research and studies to determine the feasibility of subways and inner-city expressways. Most of the highway proposals submitted by the NCTA were eventually abandoned; controversy and lawsuits slowed their development for over ten years. The subway system was not adopted in the form proposed by the NCTA, but served as the basis for the system proposed by the Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority (WMATA). WMATA succeeded the NCTA as the agency charged with implementing the Capital-region mass transit proj ect. Established in 1967 by a Charter between the governments of the District of Columbia, Maryland, and Virginia, the WMATA was granted the authority to construct, not merely advise. In this capacity, WMATA completed at least part of the work first mapped out by the NCTA.

First in 1979 and again in 1984, Stolzenbach established research projects. The first, the Metro History Project, was funded by a grant from the Mass Transportation Administration. The second, the Institute for the Study of Transportation, was a taxexempt research organization. Both projects were dedicated to writing monographs and manuscripts on the history of the highway and subway projects in the Washington area. Apparently, much of the material in Stolzenbach's collection was reorganized as he consulted it during his research.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: The C. Darwin Stolzenbach papers consists of correspondence and memoranda, bound and unbound reports, original and photocopied news clippings, documents related to civil action suits pertaining to highway legislation, excerpts from law review magazines, press releases, copies of speeches, minutes and agendas of meetings, original and photocopied Congressional and other legislation, photographs, and maps.

As a source of information about the history of the local highway and mass transit systems, this collection is invaluable. Though it is in parts incomplete and eclectic, it has a very broad range of material relating to nearly all facets of the development of highways in the Washington metropolitan area from the late 1950's to the early 1970's, and many valuable documents on the establishment of the Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Regulation Compact between the State of Maryland, the District of Columbia, and the Commonwealth of Virginia from 1963 to 1967. The collection includes an exhaustive set of local-area newspaper clippings.

While pre-dating the Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority (WMATA), the successor to the NCTA, the collection has copies of agreements, resolutions, and legislation that established the Authority. The NCTA was deeply involved in the development of the proposed Interstate 266 and the Three Sisters Bridge, and the collection has an exhaustive collection of maps, correspondence, news clippings, and civil action suits relating to these projects. And, because many documents were filed as evidence in these civil suits, the collection is rich in related documents that would not have otherwise crossed Stolzenbach's desk.

As Administrator of the NCTA, Stolzenbach acquired copies of important legislation and studies of parking and highways dating from the 1930's and 1940's. In collecting related material for the preparation of his history monographs and manuscripts, Stolzenbach also accumulated many reports and manuscripts on the history of highways and the Metro. Because of this, the collection as a whole presents an unusually comprehensive general history of highway and transportation legislation in the Washington area.

The dates of the documents in this collection range from 1876 (reproduced in a later publication) to 1988. The bulk of the documents date from 1961 to 1966. Most of the correspondence dates from 1961 through 1965, when Darwin Stolzenbach served as Administrator of the National Capital Transportation Agency (NCTA). During and subsequent to his term at the Agency, Stolzenbach collected a broad range of information related to the development of highways and public transportation, with an emphasis on those developments in the Washington metropolitan area, as well as documents related to the projects of the NCTA.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into four series: Administrator, NCTA; President METRO 2001; Director IST; and Miscellaneous.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series covers Darwin Stolzenbach's term as NCTA Administrator. However, many documents pre- and post-date this time period. Those that were created prior to 1961 were most likely acquired by Stolzenbach during his tenure, to serve as background reference. Those that date from 1966 onward are apparently from collections acquired by Stolzenbach. That material which is considered consistent with documents dating from 1961-1965, such as correspondence and court decisions, are maintained in this series. Other material that, as a group, extends beyond Stolzenbach's tenure is located in the Director, IST series.

Correspondence in the series is arranged chronologically by year, dates from 1961 to 1966 and contains Stolzenbach's own and others' letters related to the subway, highways, and general transportation, as well as NCTA administration. The Court Decisions series, arranged alphabetically by title and dating from 1876 to 1972, consists of excerpts from law review journals on various recent and historical court decisions.

The legislation material, pre-1966, is arranged alphabetically and consists of bound and loose Congressional Record extracts, reports and summaries, testimony, and other Government Printing Office documents chronicling Federal, State, and District involvement in the development of Metro and Interstate Highways. Maps are arranged by title. These are mostly technical in layouts, but include topographical maps with proposed subway routes drawn on them.
Material related to meetings, agendas and minutes are arranged chronologically and contains documents from meetings of the NCTA and other organizations.

There are also miscellaneous materials that are arranged alphabetically by folder title and consist of a variety of items including contract information. Additionally, press releases are arranged chronologically and consist of draft, original, and copy news releases from the NCTA, private, and Federal organizations.

The material related to public hearings are arranged alphabetically and are made up of hearings on the proposed I-266 route and the Three Sisters Bridge. Reports, which are arranged alphabetically, are a wide variety of bound and unbound reports, printed and typewritten, for both in-house and general use. Subject matter is generally confined to research and studies of highway and mass transit proposals.

Speeches are arranged chronologically and consist of original and copy typescript sheets or summary notes of public and private speeches by civil and Government officials on various transportation-related topics, including testimony before Congressional committees.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains documents related to Stolzenbach's association with the Metro History Project (MHP) established by WMATA. The documents include computer-generated indexes used in the MHP, transcripts of MHP oral histories, and correspondence.
Correspondence in the series are ordered chronologically and consists of correspondence related to research for the Metro History Project.

The material related to the MHP chapter drafts is arranged numerically by chapter, therein alphabetically by type of document. Material consists of computer-generated lists arranging cited documents by categories.

The material related to the MHP document abstracts is arraigned alphabetical by title of abstract index and also consists of computer-generated cross-referenced indexes containing all the MHP Abstract documents.
The material related to the MHP monographs is arranged alphabetically by title and contains copies of the three "Metro History Monographs" written by Stolzenbach and Elizabeth Durham.
MHP oral history transcripts are arranged alphabetically by interviewee. The transcripts are often excerpted or paraphrased, and the format of the documents varies.
There is also miscellaneous material series arranged alphabetical by folder title.

This series contains computer-generated indexes and transcripts that generally duplicate those found in the WMATA Metro History Project Collection. The Monographs are a good source of general historical background, as are the chapter drafts themselves, which apparently served as rough sketches of important concepts.

Metro 2001 was established in 1979, the beginning dates in this series. The ending date of the MHP, and the date of dissolution of Metro 2001 are unknown (hence their absence from the record group title). However, to avoid overlap, documents in this series do not post-date 1984, when the 1ST was founded.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The documents in this series relate to Stolzenbach's research into the history of the highway projects of the NCTA and other federal agencies. The collection includes reports and proposals by other agencies, as well as a copy of a manuscript on Metro history, written by an independent researcher. Stolzenbach used the bulk of his collection, as well as material in other series, for writing the reports contained in this series.

Administrative Documents series are arranged alphabetically by type of document, therein in chronological order. Included are documents relating to tax-exempt status, office rental, meeting minutes, and other duties of the IST.

Correspondence is arranged chronologically and consists primarily of Stolzenbach's letters to interviewees and other IST executive officers. The manuscript by Booth Mooney entitled "Metro: Building Rapid Rail Transit in the National Capital Region" is arranged in page order. The Department of Special Collections has also a bound version of this document as a separately-cataloged item.

Newspaper clippings and articles are arranged chronologically; this is a small collection of contemporary news extracts. Notes, handwritten and typed, consist of written and typed notes taken by Stolzenbach related to telephone conversations, references, or ideas for chapters.

Project proposals are arranged chronologically followed by undated material. These items are made up IST letters to various agencies describing the research to be undertaken. Project Reports are chronologically arranged, being reports generated by IST outlining project progress.
Reports by other agencies are arranged alphabetically by name of agency. These include proposals to undertake research work for the IST.

Mooney's manuscript is a good general reference to the history of Metro. This series contains little of a historical nature, but does serve to illustrate the workings of the IST and the state of Interstate and transportation-related history from 1984 to 1988.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains documents post-dating Stolzenbach's service as Administrator of the NCTA. Some of the material dates from the 1961-1965 period as well, such as in the cases of the Newspaper Clippings and Civil Action Suits. These were determined to be distinct collections in their own right and were thus kept intact.

The Civil Action Suits materials are arranged chronologically by year the suit began and therein by suit number. Included are petitions, evidence, testimony, charges, and counter-suits for several famous and many less-famous Interstate-related civil suits brought against the Department of Transportation between 1960 and 1975.

Legislation, post-1966 is arranged alphabetically by title, and follows the Legislation, pre-1966 material in the Administrator, NCTA series of bound and unbound official transcripts of Congressional proceedings.

Miscellaneous materials are arranged alphabetically. Newspaper clippings are arranged chronologically. This items include clippings primarily from local papers related to transportation issues in the area.
Oversize Reports, consisting of bound and printed reports, are organized by title. Public hearings, post-1966 are arranged by title and relate primarily to the hearings on the proposed 1-266 route.
The reading files are organized alphabetically by name of the name of the person. Included are correspondence files generated by the various originators and apparently donated to Stolzenbach.
Reports are arranged alphabetically by title. Included are bound and unbound reports generated by various authorities, primarily related to the WMATA and the Metro system.

The material related to civil action suits contains complete, or nearly-complete, documentation of famous individual cases such as the Three Sisters Bridge case, and may be assumed to be one of the few complete collections of these documents.
Newspaper clippings are the large and exhaustive group. They are valuable for their comprehensive coverage of general trends, issues, and concerns relating to highway development and mass transit.
